	<h2>Introduction:</h2>
	This lab exercises the ability to use <b>Conditional Repetition</b>.
	<h2>Lab Assignment:</h2>

	<p> 

	Using <tt> <a href="http://balance3e.com/Ch13/repstats.html">repstats.html</a>
	</tt> from Reed's
	<a href="http://balance3e.com/source.html">resource page</a>,<br>
	Implement Exercises:
	<ol>
	    <li>13.6 &amp; 13.7</li>
	    <ul>
		    <li>The <u>number of rolls</u> should be a <u>multiple</u> of <b>36</b>. (<i>this is so that the expected number of rolls of any specified value is a whole number</i>)<br>
			Modify the textbox label to read: "<tt>Desired number of rolls (&times;36):</tt>"<br>
			Your loop will execute <b>36 times</b> the value entered by the user into the textbox.<br>
			[The "<tt>&times;</tt>" symbol is written with "<tt>&amp;times;</tt>"]</li>
		<li>Display the expected frequency (how many times out of 36) and both the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relative_error">absolute &amp; relative error</a> from the expected frequency.</li>
	    </ul>
	    <li>13.17</li>
	</ol>
	<p>

	When finished:
	<ul>
	    <li>After testing thoroughly, submit your exercises 13.7 &amp; 13.17 solution Web pages to the dropbox.</li>
	    <li>Also, submit a screenshot of each, following their respective execution, to the dropbox.
	</ul>

